Here's the full audit of `OrderProcessorTests.cs`:

---

## 📊 Summary Dashboard

| Severity | Smell Count | Affected Tests |
|----------|-------------|----------------|
| 🔴 High | 4 | 4 |
| 🟡 Medium | 5 | 4 |
| 🔵 Low | 1 | 1 (class-level) |
| **Total** | **10** | **8 of 9 tests** |

Only `ValidateOrder_NullOrder_ThrowsArgumentNullException` is clean.

---

## 🔴 High Severity

### 1. Conditional Test Logic — `ProcessOrder_SetsCorrectStatus` (line 31)
The `if/else` means **one branch never executes** per run. You think both statuses are covered — they aren't.
```csharp
// ❌ Today
if (result.TotalAmount > 100)
    Assert.AreEqual("PremiumProcessed", result.Status);
else
    Assert.AreEqual("StandardProcessed", result.Status);

// ✅ Fix: split into two tests with deterministic inputs
[TestMethod]
public void ProcessOrder_StandardOrder_SetsStandardStatus()
{
    var order = new Order { Items = { new OrderItem("SKU-CHEAP", 1) } };
    var result = processor.ProcessOrder(order);
    Assert.AreEqual("StandardProcessed", result.Status);
}
```

### 2. Assertion-Free Test — `ProcessOrder_CompletesWithoutError` (line 43)
No assertions at all. If `ProcessOrder` silently returns garbage, this test passes. It provides **false coverage**.
```csharp
// ❌ Today — passes even if everything is broken
processor.ProcessOrder(order);

// ✅ Fix: assert the expected outcome
var result = processor.ProcessOrder(order);
Assert.AreEqual("StandardProcessed", result.Status);
Assert.IsTrue(_db.WasOrderSaved(order.Id));
```

### 3. Sleepy Test — `ProcessOrder_AsyncNotification_IsSent` (line 98)
`Thread.Sleep(2000)` makes this slow and flaky. If the system is under load, 2 seconds may not be enough; on a fast machine, it wastes time.
```csharp
// ❌ Today
processor.ProcessOrderAsync(order);
Thread.Sleep(2000);
Assert.IsTrue(_email.WasNotificationSent(order.Id));

// ✅ Fix: await the async operation, or poll with a timeout
await processor.ProcessOrderAsync(order);
Assert.IsTrue(_email.WasNotificationSent(order.Id));
```

### 4. Mystery Guest — `ImportOrders_FromCsv_ParsesCorrectly` (line 144)
Hard-coded path `C:\TestData\orders.csv` creates an invisible dependency. This test **will fail** on any machine that doesn't have that exact file — including CI.
```csharp
// ❌ Today
var orders = processor.ImportOrders(
    File.ReadAllText(@"C:\TestData\orders.csv"));

// ✅ Fix: inline the test data
const string csv = """
    SKU-1,2,49.99
    SKU-2,1,19.99
    """;
var orders = processor.ImportOrders(csv);
Assert.AreEqual(2, orders.Count);
```

---

## 🟡 Medium Severity

### 5. Eager Test — `OrderProcessor_FullWorkflow_Succeeds` (line 54)
